## Clear Creek Canyon Navigation

The route to Black Hawk follows Highway 6 west through Clear Creek Canyon, then Highway 119 north through the canyon system to reach the historic mining district. This canyon route creates operational constraints that affect every transportation decision.

The canyon road system allows only two-lane traffic through most sections, with limited passing opportunities and no alternate routes when problems occur. Construction projects, accident scenes, or disabled vehicles create complete traffic stoppages that can last 30-90 minutes.

Seasonal rockslide activity presents ongoing hazards. [The Colorado Geological Survey](https://coloradogeologicalsurvey.org/) monitors slope stability throughout the canyon system, but rock debris reaches the roadway regularly during spring snowmelt and summer storm periods. Transportation providers need contingency plans for route closures that can happen without advance warning.

Winter driving conditions make the canyon treacherous for inexperienced drivers. Black ice forms in shadowed canyon sections while sunny areas remain dry, creating variable conditions within short distances. Commercial transportation requires drivers with mountain driving experience and vehicles equipped for winter conditions.

